Here are the MSTest patterns for each scenario:

**1. Windows-only (platform restriction)**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)] // custom attribute, or:
public void RegistryTest()
{
    if (!RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.Windows))
        Assert.Inconclusive("Requires Windows");
    // ... registry code
}
```

**2. Skip in CI (environment-based skip)**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GpuTest()
{
    if (Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("CI") == "true")
        Assert.Inconclusive("Skipped in CI — requires local GPU");
    // ... GPU test
}
```

**3. Flaky external API (retry pattern)**

```csharp
// MSTest v3+ has [Retry]:
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)] // retries up to 3 times on failure
public void WeatherApiTest()
{
    var result = CallWeatherApi();
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

For older MSTest without `[Retry]`, catch transient failures manually:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void WeatherApiTest()
{
    Exception last = null;
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++)
    {
        try { CallWeatherApi(); return; }
        catch (Exception ex) { last = ex; Thread.Sleep(1000); }
    }
    Assert.Fail($"Failed after 3 attempts: {last?.Message}");
}
```

**4. Cleanup even on failure (use `[TestCleanup]` or `try/finally`)**

```csharp
private string _tempFile;

[TestInitialize]
public void Setup()
{
    _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
}

[TestCleanup] // runs even if the test fails
public void Cleanup()
{
    if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
        File.Delete(_tempFile);
}

[TestMethod]
public void FileProcessingTest()
{
    File.WriteAllText(_tempFile, "data");
    // ... assertions
}
```

**Key takeaways:**

| Scenario | Approach |
|---|---|
| Platform gate | `Assert.Inconclusive()` or custom condition attribute |
| Environment gate | Check env vars → `Assert.Inconclusive()` |
| Flaky tests | `[Retry(N)]` (MSTest v3+) |
| Guaranteed cleanup | `[TestCleanup]` — always runs, even on failure |

`Assert.Inconclusive()` is preferred over `[Ignore]` because it still executes conditionally and shows up as a warning in results rather than being silently skipped.
